  "prompt": "How can evaporated milk be substituted for condensed milk?",
  "response": "Substituting evaporated milk for condensed milk requires some adjustments because they are quite different in terms of sweetness and consistency. Condensed milk is sweetened and thick, while evaporated milk is unsweetened and has a thinner consistency. Here\u2019s how you can make the substitution:\n\n### **Option 1: Add Sugar to Evaporated Milk**\n1. Use 1 cup of **evaporated milk**.\n2. Mix it with **1 1/4 cups of granulated sugar**.\n3. Heat the mixture gently on the stove, stirring until the sugar dissolves completely.\n4. Let it cool before using. This will approximate the sweetness and thickness of condensed milk.\n\n### **Option 2: Use Evaporated Milk with a Sweetener**\nIf you don\u2019t want to add granulated sugar, you can use a sweetener like honey, maple syrup, or a liquid sweetener. Adjust the quantity based on your taste preference.\n\n### **Option 3: Use Evaporated Milk as a Lower-Sugar Alternative**\nIf you\u2019re okay with a less sweet result, you can use **evaporated milk** directly in place of condensed milk, but note that the recipe will be less sweet and the texture may differ.\n\n### **Note:**\n- These substitutions work best in recipes where the consistency and sweetness of condensed milk aren\u2019t critical (e.g., in beverages or sauces).\n- For recipes like fudge or desserts where condensed milk is a key ingredient, the substitution might not yield the exact same results.\n\nIf you\u2019re looking for a non-dairy alternative, coconut milk or plant-based creams sweetened with sugar can also be used in similar ways.",
